carried out\nusing the double-exponential over a semi-finite interval method. In both\nmethods a precision of $10^{-15}$ is adopted. {\\bf Results.} The total internal\nenergy of the plasma is mainly dominated by the ionization energy for\ntemperatures lower than $8\\times 10^4$ K with the excitation energy having a\ncontribution of less than one percent. In thermal and non-thermal plasmas\ncomposed of H, He, and metals, the adiabatic parameter evolution is determined\nby the H and He ionizations leading to a profile in general having three\ntransitions. However, for $\\kappa$ distributed plasmas these three transitions\nare not observed for $\\kappa<15$ (...). In general, $\\gamma$ varies from 1.01\nto 5/3.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 2 May 2018 12:36:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-15"}
